Connect, support and empower: how Cruxing In Color makes climbing more accessible: *link in bio

1) Climbers at Shelf Road pick out a warm-up during a Cruxing In Color/Climb United meet up in October. 📸 Dally Tram @dallyhue 
2) Menesha Mannapperuma, CIC co-founder with Shara Zaia, climbing at the Terrain Boulders in the Flatirons. 📸 James Lucas (@james_lucas)
3) One of CIC’s monthly meetups - this one at The Spot in Golden, April 2021. 
📸 Dally Tram @dallyhue
Drew Smith cruises Table Manners (5.9) at The Grotto, just one of many basalt crags near Sonora, California.

Sofia Gonzalez redpoints Sidesaddle (5.9), her first ever lead climb, at The Grotto. Heather belays with Dallas asleep on her back. 
*link in bio for more on our quirky sport climbing vacation.

Occasionally, timing works out just right. 
Heather and I both had goals for our 3.5-week sport climbing trip to CA. Incredibly, we both squeaked them in - me on our 2nd to last day, and Heather in the 2nd to last hour! 
I’m especially proud of Heather, who, less than 1 year after giving birth to our son Dallas, sent her 14a project. 
For a moment it appeared she might crack under the pressure, but she somehow overcame her darkness and doubts to climb as well as I’ve ever seen her climb.

Solid as a rock? How climbing can shatter our illusion of permanence. *Link in bio for story.
Matt Segal on the Tom Egan Memorial Route (5.14) - one of a dozen climbs that came crashing down when most of the Tom Egan Wall on Snowpatch Spire in the Bugaboos collapsed 2 weeks ago. 📸 Tim Kemple @timkemple

A farewell to Dave Turner: climber, skier, family man, lawyer and coffee fiend. *link in bio for story

1) Dave leading Deviant (5.9+) in Eldorado Canyon back in April 2012. “A typical day in Dave’s remarkable life,” said Bill Briggs, Dave’s good friend and one of his climbing partners that day. 📸 Bill Briggs
2) Celebrating his 70th birthday last July. “We decorated each Doubleshot with birthday wishes and photos of him throughout his 70 years,” said his daughters, Stephanie and May. 📸 Nancy Turner
Katie Ives leading some Front Range ice yesterday.

The scariest decision of my life: link in bio for story.

1) Heather on Du Opfa (5.13) in Leonidio, Greece. At the time she wrestled internally with her desire for a kid, but was too afraid to tell me. 
2) Being a dad has its perks. Dallas finds joy in the simplest things, he’s an open book without fear of judgement, and he makes me laugh every single day.

The Green ‘23 started off a bit… chilly.

Spring break on the Green River. In some ways it was the least productive of our 12-ish trips to Labyrinth Canyon. Cold, wet, snowy weather prevented climbing half our days. But we still nabbed a few FAs, including this tower we’d had our eye on since 2010.
Photos 2 and 3: 📸 @celinserbo

Celin pioneered this intimidating splitter that was, thankfully, not as wide as it appeared from the ground. He put in anchors and we TRd and brushed and cleaned a bit, but an unforecasted snowstorm prevented the send. Until next time…

TV Star, Cat Runner, on climbing, male privilege and being trans: link in bio for story 
1)Cat attempts “Boys Don’t Cry” (5.13a) in Siurana, Spain during the second episode of The Climb. 📸 courtesy HBO Max
2)Cat speaking on the Allies panel, a cohort of men and folks who identify as male, during the No Man’s Land Film Festival in Denver last month. 📸 Emily Trombly

Celin Serbo on the first ascent of Chonchito (5.10), and nearing the top of The Dallas Phallus, high above the Green River in March.
Happy birthday buddy!

A bit of DWS on the Big Island last weekend. I’m always more nervous than I feel like I should be 🤷🏻‍♂️
📸 Sofia Gonzalez

Happy birthday to this adventurous mama! As time and milestones keep  passing, Heather is at least as driven as she’s always been. I’m so impressed by how she balances motherhood, climbing and the rest of life. Here’s to another wonderful year! ❤️

Summit or plummet: one magazine’s whimsical courage lives on. 
Summit Journal is the latest iteration of the original Summit Magazine, which was started by two daring women who thrived against the grain. 

*Link in bio for story

1) A 1988 cover of Summit Magazine featuring the famous free-hanging rappel off the west side of The Maiden in the Flatirons. 
2) Jean Crenshaw, one of the two women who launched and published Summit Magazine from 1955 through 1989.
3) Helen Kilness and the motorcycle she and Crenshaw rode across the country back in 1946.
4) Michael Levy, the new editor and publisher of Summit Journal, sport climbing at 14,000 feet in Hatun Machay, Peru in 2021. 📸 Levi Harrell

Chalk, sticky rubber, hangdogging, kneepads - at one point all were considered cheating in climbing, but are now all but universally viewed as legitimate. You never know, today’s controversy could be tomorrow’s breakthrough: 
*link in bio for story
📸 Bruce Miller solo TR-ing the first of two 5.13 pitches on what would soon become Gambler’s Fallacy (5.13b) on the Diamond of Longs Peak. The kneebar, for which we used a kneepad on the send, proved crucial for this sequence.
